00:01:41.390 --> 00:01:48.000
So when I was 21, I
lost my best friend.

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:52.860
He was also my brother.

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:57.010
He was 24 when he died.

00:01:57.010 --> 00:01:59.860
And many of you know the story.

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:03.980
His name was Chris McCandless.

00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:08.630
He had graduated with
honors from Emory University

00:02:08.630 --> 00:02:15.230
and that was the last time
that I had ever seen him alive,

00:02:15.230 --> 00:02:17.530
it was the last time I'd spoken.

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:22.620
He had written me letters,
but I hadn't spoken to him

00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:25.590
since seeing him at graduation.

00:02:25.590 --> 00:02:30.542
Two years later,
his body was found

00:02:30.542 --> 00:02:32.000
in this abandoned
bus in the middle

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.590
of the Alaskan wilderness.

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:37.382
There was a lot of
mystery surrounding

00:02:37.382 --> 00:02:39.840
his death and everything that
had happened during those two

00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:41.340
years.

00:02:41.340 --> 00:02:46.490
And the story of that time
and all of the adventures

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:50.510
that he had during
that time became

00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:54.260
known as "Into
the Wild," as such

00:02:54.260 --> 00:02:58.940
summarized the incredible
book written by Jon Krakauer.

00:02:58.940 --> 00:03:02.660
And then it was also developed
into a film by Sean Penn.

00:03:02.660 --> 00:03:04.970
And Chris' story really became--

00:03:04.970 --> 00:03:07.160
I mean, John's book
was so popular it's

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:11.340
published in over 30 languages.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:17.300
Sean's movie, also so
beautiful, and Chris' story

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:21.020
reached even more of
a global audience.

00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:24.930
But it wasn't the whole story.

00:03:28.950 --> 00:03:31.790
So to give you a
little back story,

00:03:31.790 --> 00:03:34.580
this is Chris with the
Shenandoah behind him.

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:36.710
We used to hike a lot--
this is my hiking hat--

00:03:40.210 --> 00:03:40.990
in that area.

00:03:40.990 --> 00:03:45.940
And he loves to
be out in nature.

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:48.700
Chris always said
to me that nature

00:03:48.700 --> 00:03:52.770
may be harsh in its honesty,
but it never lies to you.

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:53.490
And he felt--

00:03:56.940 --> 00:04:00.120
I don't know, he felt
whole, he felt real

00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:02.340
when he was out in nature.

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:07.070
And I just remember it was
always his favorite place

00:04:07.070 --> 00:04:07.680
to be.

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:10.160
It was always an escape for
him, even at this young age.

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:14.700
Chris and I were very close.

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:15.920
He was always my protector.

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:23.250
It's a cute picture, right?

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:23.750
All right.

00:04:23.750 --> 00:04:27.000
This picture tells a story.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:32.590
This picture was taken
on a typical morning.

00:04:32.590 --> 00:04:38.640
Our house was on an
everyday basis filled

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:45.740
with domestic violence and this
day was not unlike any other.

00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:48.770
The violence had erupted
over the breakfast table

00:04:48.770 --> 00:04:50.520
and continued on until
my parents realized

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:52.700
that it was time for church.

00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:55.774
It was Easter Sunday so
we were put into our best

00:04:55.774 --> 00:04:57.190
suit and dress and
we were marched

00:04:57.190 --> 00:05:00.930
into the backyard for pictures.

00:05:00.930 --> 00:05:13.910
And pictures, they catch
an image in time, right,

00:05:13.910 --> 00:05:16.230
but you don't really
know what's going on.

00:05:16.230 --> 00:05:19.050
You don't know the whole
story behind the image.

00:05:19.050 --> 00:05:24.730
And whenever we
would have to pause

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:31.310
for the perfect little
family pictures,

00:05:31.310 --> 00:05:34.430
our dad would behind the
camera screaming at us smile.

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:36.250
Smile.

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:38.820
So what we had just been
through in the household,

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:41.440
really not in the mood
but you had to do it.

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:44.390
And if you didn't, I knew
what was coming next.

00:05:44.390 --> 00:05:48.540
Now, look closely at our
expressions in these pictures.

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:53.640
So I'm being compliant,
I've got a smile on my face.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:55.230
I've got my hand
behind his back,

00:05:55.230 --> 00:06:01.470
I'm trying to convince Chris
smile, let's get this done.

00:06:01.470 --> 00:06:05.490
And look at the look on his
face if you really look closely.

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:09.310
He's only about
six years old here,

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:11.560
but he's already
older than that.

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:12.910
He already understands.

00:06:12.910 --> 00:06:15.910
Now, what's really important
about this picture--

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:17.379
I've got it on the
cover of my book

00:06:17.379 --> 00:06:19.420
because people look at
that and they're like, oh,

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:21.280
that's such a sweet picture.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:25.710
But again, it's the point of
the story behind the images

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:27.360
that we see, right?

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:30.220
That's what this whole
talk is going to be about.

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:38.030
And I can remember it
like it was yesterday.

00:06:38.030 --> 00:06:41.510
You have this image that
you're going to portray out

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:45.230
to society, but sometimes
it's so very different

00:06:45.230 --> 00:06:48.420
from what is actually going on.

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:56.750
So Chris just, even at that age
he wasn't going to accept that.

00:06:56.750 --> 00:07:02.270
He was already planning.

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:05.840
He was already at
that young age making

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:08.510
a determination of what's
right and what's wrong.

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:12.260
When you grow up in a
household of domestic violence,

00:07:12.260 --> 00:07:14.090
you become acclimated to it.

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:16.940
You don't know at this
age that every household

00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:18.650
isn't like that.

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:20.120
You don't understand.

00:07:20.120 --> 00:07:24.260
So when your environment
is saturated with that,

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:27.590
you become completely
desensitized to it.

00:07:27.590 --> 00:07:30.590
Chris understood
something was wrong.

00:07:30.590 --> 00:07:38.420
Now, as we grew up,
in a lot of ways

00:07:38.420 --> 00:07:40.970
Chris was your typical
kid, but in other ways

00:07:40.970 --> 00:07:43.310
there was just
something about him

00:07:43.310 --> 00:07:47.750
that I don't know you could
say was deeper than most people

00:07:47.750 --> 00:07:49.080
at that age.

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:52.830
And sometimes we would
just be having typical kid

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:56.730
conversations or we would be
fighting over that's my space

00:07:56.730 --> 00:08:00.130
or don't come in my room,
but other times we'd

00:08:00.130 --> 00:08:03.210
be having these conversations
about an author or something

00:08:03.210 --> 00:08:07.980
that he just read that he wanted
me to read or big questions

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:10.440
and I was more interested
in the stuffed animals

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:13.140
at that age or makeup
at a later age.

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:16.250
Chris was different.

00:08:16.250 --> 00:08:18.650
At this age, he was
already thinking

00:08:18.650 --> 00:08:24.380
a lot about who he
wanted to be and probably

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:27.290
most importantly, who
he would not become.

00:08:29.850 --> 00:08:36.304
So John's book became
required reading.

00:08:36.304 --> 00:08:37.929
"Into the Wild" became
required reading

00:08:37.929 --> 00:08:40.330
at about 3,000 high
schools and colleges

00:08:40.330 --> 00:08:42.549
across the United States.

00:08:42.549 --> 00:08:44.450
John doesn't like to
do public speaking

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:47.320
so he would suggest me.

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:50.770
And it took me a very,
very, very long time

00:08:50.770 --> 00:08:55.780
to get to the point where I felt
comfortable going and speaking

00:08:55.780 --> 00:08:59.550
to people about Chris' story.

00:08:59.550 --> 00:09:04.910
And when I did, I would
be talking to students

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:06.570
who are about this age.

00:09:06.570 --> 00:09:10.130
This is Chris' typical senior
picture in high school, right?

00:09:10.130 --> 00:09:13.520
And when I came
to the school, you

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:15.020
would see a change
in these students

00:09:15.020 --> 00:09:19.510
because it became real to them.

00:09:19.510 --> 00:09:21.190
It was no longer
just an assignment,

00:09:21.190 --> 00:09:23.890
it was this lesson because
this is a real flesh and blood

00:09:23.890 --> 00:09:26.400
sister of this person.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:32.000
And it wasn't just that
I could see that they

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.377
were inspired by Chris.

00:09:34.377 --> 00:09:35.960
There's usually two
camps, some people

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:38.330
admired him for what he did,
some people admonished him.

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:39.788
That's part of the
reason that it's

00:09:39.788 --> 00:09:42.290
something that's assigned,
right, because they want people

00:09:42.290 --> 00:09:44.570
to get into that
critical kind of thinking

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:46.710
and think outside of themselves.

00:09:46.710 --> 00:09:54.085
But what hit me more was that
I never left one school--

00:09:56.750 --> 00:09:59.196
first of all, they always
asked about the back story,

00:09:59.196 --> 00:10:01.570
right, which at first I wasn't
necessarily talking about.

00:10:01.570 --> 00:10:04.337
But in the Q&amp;A, that's always
what the questions were--

00:10:04.337 --> 00:10:05.920
why was he so angry
with your parents,

00:10:05.920 --> 00:10:08.140
why did he leave the way
he did, why didn't he

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:11.830
talk to anybody for those
years after he left college?

00:10:11.830 --> 00:10:15.340
And when I opened up in the
safety of the intimate walls

00:10:15.340 --> 00:10:20.850
of a classroom where things
weren't recorded yet,

00:10:20.850 --> 00:10:24.270
I saw this change come
over the students,

00:10:24.270 --> 00:10:25.470
and some in particular.

00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:29.087
Because I never left one
school, and still to this day

00:10:29.087 --> 00:10:30.670
all the years that
I've been speaking,

00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:34.800
I've never left one school, one
university a corporate event,

00:10:34.800 --> 00:10:39.060
I've never left anywhere where
at least one person didn't

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:40.282
come up.

00:10:40.282 --> 00:10:42.840
And in this case, it was
these high school students

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:47.240
that didn't come up and ask for
help for the very first time

00:10:47.240 --> 00:10:49.950
because they were going
through a similar experience

00:10:49.950 --> 00:10:54.400
and here was someone
talking about it.

00:10:54.400 --> 00:11:02.720
So after years of doing this and
seeing this everywhere I went,

00:11:02.720 --> 00:11:06.926
I realized what a disservice
I had done to my brother--

00:11:06.926 --> 00:11:09.300
and not just to Chris, but
those who would read about him

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:10.350
and be inspired by him.

00:11:10.350 --> 00:11:12.660
Because Chris always
said there is nothing

00:11:12.660 --> 00:11:15.200
more important than the truth.

00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:18.770
And John did an job
writing "Into the Wild."

00:11:18.770 --> 00:11:21.140
and what was left
out of it is my fault

00:11:21.140 --> 00:11:24.800
because I wanted
John to understand,

00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:27.700
but I wouldn't let
him write that.

00:11:30.800 --> 00:11:32.300
I wasn't ready.

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:33.920
And I realized
later on, wow, what

00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:36.230
a disservice I had done to
such an incredible writer

00:11:36.230 --> 00:11:38.105
and someone with that
journalistic style, Jon

00:11:38.105 --> 00:11:40.687
Krakauer, to give
them information

00:11:40.687 --> 00:11:43.020
but tell him beforehand, I'm
going to tell you something

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:46.010
but my condition is you're
not allowed to reveal this.

00:11:46.010 --> 00:11:47.510
I just need you to know.

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:51.770
I didn't think anybody was
going to read "Into the Wild,"

00:11:51.770 --> 00:11:58.220
so it's kind of Jon's
fault. So anyway, I

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:01.320
realized what a disservice I had
done by not talking about this.

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:03.820
And here 20 years has passed.

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:07.240
So as I mentioned earlier,
I journal all the time.

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:09.580
Chris was the one that
taught me to journal

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:11.840
and we'll get a little
bit more into that.

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:15.300
But I just started writing.

00:12:15.300 --> 00:12:20.860
And all of those journal
entries turned into a book.

00:12:20.860 --> 00:12:31.270
And what I didn't
expect was for my book

00:12:31.270 --> 00:12:34.750
to start a new conversation
about domestic violence.

00:12:34.750 --> 00:12:36.910
There were all these
blanks in Chris' story

00:12:36.910 --> 00:12:39.730
and people, rightfully
so, had filled

00:12:39.730 --> 00:12:43.270
in those blanks with
their own answers

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:44.890
as to why he had
left the way he did

00:12:44.890 --> 00:12:48.270
or what had happened
with the family.

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:53.030
And when my book came out, or
long before the book came out--

00:12:53.030 --> 00:12:57.560
just when I was in these rooms
of 50 people, 500 people,

00:12:57.560 --> 00:12:59.060
it didn't matter--

00:12:59.060 --> 00:13:01.640
when I would talk about
the rest of the story,

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:05.930
it forced people to take
another look at Chris' story.

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:08.360
Not in defense of him,
because in all fairness,

00:13:08.360 --> 00:13:11.549
he didn't live his life worried
about what anyone else was

00:13:11.549 --> 00:13:12.590
going to think about him.

00:13:12.590 --> 00:13:15.262
He was concerned about what
he thought about himself.

00:13:15.262 --> 00:13:21.460
But now that people had
the rest of the answers,

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:24.630
a lot of their
perspectives changed

00:13:24.630 --> 00:13:28.860
and that was not
something that I realized

00:13:28.860 --> 00:13:33.150
when I was 21 years
old and he was gone

00:13:33.150 --> 00:13:40.050
and I was having to tell
this journalist why he left.

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:50.480
So people not only would take
another look at Chris' story,

00:13:50.480 --> 00:13:52.430
but they started taking
another look at story

00:13:52.430 --> 00:13:53.471
in their own communities.

00:13:53.471 --> 00:13:55.290
And I started doing
the same thing.

00:13:55.290 --> 00:14:03.230
So whenever I was
at these schools--

00:14:03.230 --> 00:14:06.430
and for the most
part, these are--

00:14:06.430 --> 00:14:09.780
if they're hiring
a speaker to come.

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:11.630
these schools are
filled with kids

00:14:11.630 --> 00:14:15.860
who have a certain amount
of privilege, right?

00:14:15.860 --> 00:14:18.620
They're all wearing pretty
nice clothes, when I pull up

00:14:18.620 --> 00:14:21.277
to speak there's tons of
cars in the parking lot

00:14:21.277 --> 00:14:23.360
so pretty much all these
kids have access to cars,

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:30.960
they drive for school; they all
have phones, right, computers

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:32.040
and tablets.

00:14:32.040 --> 00:14:35.310
So they all want to connect
with me on social media

00:14:35.310 --> 00:14:38.340
and I've never really been
big on having a social media

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:38.850
presence.

00:14:38.850 --> 00:14:45.230
My publisher is so incredibly
kind and patient with me

00:14:45.230 --> 00:14:49.640
for you're really supposed
to be on a lot and I'm not.

00:14:49.640 --> 00:14:52.670
But I do try and make an effort.

00:14:52.670 --> 00:14:55.490
And for the most
part, it's when I'm

00:14:55.490 --> 00:14:57.414
connecting with these
students because I want

00:14:57.414 --> 00:14:58.580
to stay connected with them.

00:14:58.580 --> 00:15:00.097
I want to see what
they're doing.

00:15:00.097 --> 00:15:02.180
I want to see what they're
doing with their lives.

00:15:02.180 --> 00:15:05.007
I want to hear what
they're doing next.

00:15:05.007 --> 00:15:06.590
Because they'll tell
me their stories.

00:15:06.590 --> 00:15:08.548
They'll tell me how they
were inspired by Chris

00:15:08.548 --> 00:15:10.350
and what they want to do.

00:15:10.350 --> 00:15:16.230
But as I am looking at the
social media of these kids

00:15:16.230 --> 00:15:18.520
that I've connected with--

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:20.950
