00:43:17.286 --> 00:43:18.660
you want to do
things differently

00:43:18.660 --> 00:43:20.400
than your parents
did, for example.

00:43:20.400 --> 00:43:20.530
CARINE MCCANDLESS: Yeah.

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:21.880
And my parents weren't all bad.

00:43:21.880 --> 00:43:22.790
I mean, they weren't.

00:43:22.790 --> 00:43:25.120
And I talk about that and
I flush it out in my book.

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:28.870
They taught us some
hard work ethics

00:43:28.870 --> 00:43:30.280
and a lot of good things, too.

00:43:30.280 --> 00:43:33.327
But you have to decide what
you're going to emulate

00:43:33.327 --> 00:43:34.160
and what you're not.

00:43:34.160 --> 00:43:36.550
And specifically on the
issue of domestic violence,

00:43:36.550 --> 00:43:39.520
breaking that cycle is
a very important thing

00:43:39.520 --> 00:43:41.460
and it's not easy to do.

00:43:41.460 --> 00:43:45.250
SACHIT EGAN: And so
in that same vein,

00:43:45.250 --> 00:43:47.440
you talk about some examples
with your own daughters

00:43:47.440 --> 00:43:52.660
of how you try to embody
authenticity, positive thoughts

00:43:52.660 --> 00:43:55.360
around relationships and around
the relationship with the self.

00:43:55.360 --> 00:43:57.490
I know a lot of parents
are either in this room

00:43:57.490 --> 00:43:58.980
or watching on livestream.

00:43:58.980 --> 00:44:00.745
Do have any thoughts
or tips around how

00:44:00.745 --> 00:44:02.680
to embody these values
in your own family?

00:44:02.680 --> 00:44:03.680
CARINE MCCANDLESS: Sure.

00:44:03.680 --> 00:44:09.160
And I'm not standing up here
like, hey, I'm doing it right

00:44:09.160 --> 00:44:10.720
and everyone has
got to get on board.

00:44:10.720 --> 00:44:11.710
No, no, no, no.

00:44:11.710 --> 00:44:13.750
My 18-year-old, I love her.

00:44:13.750 --> 00:44:15.199
She is such a good kid.

00:44:15.199 --> 00:44:16.990
I have an 18-year-old
daughter that's never

00:44:16.990 --> 00:44:20.900
rolled her eyes at me in my
presence or slammed a door,

00:44:20.900 --> 00:44:21.670
right?

00:44:21.670 --> 00:44:22.180
Miracle.

00:44:22.180 --> 00:44:24.640
Is it because I'm such
an amazing parent?

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:25.690
I'd like to think so.

00:44:25.690 --> 00:44:28.450
She's probably not
going to say that.

00:44:28.450 --> 00:44:30.910
But let's take that for example.

00:44:30.910 --> 00:44:35.200
I take my kids to my events
and sometimes things sink

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:37.330
in and sometimes they don't.

00:44:37.330 --> 00:44:40.082
My oldest, she came up
from the basement one night

00:44:40.082 --> 00:44:42.040
and I was sitting working
at the kitchen table.

00:44:42.040 --> 00:44:43.831
And she came up and I
might get off tangent

00:44:43.831 --> 00:44:45.150
and you can reel me back in.

00:44:45.150 --> 00:44:49.660
But she came up from watching
a TV show just blubbering.

00:44:49.660 --> 00:44:54.620
I mean, she was crying so
hard that she couldn't speak.

00:44:54.620 --> 00:44:55.120
And

00:44:55.120 --> 00:44:56.710
I'm like oh my God,
Heather, what's the matter?

00:44:56.710 --> 00:44:57.293
What happened?

00:44:57.293 --> 00:44:58.120
What's wrong?

00:44:58.120 --> 00:45:00.495
I can't-- I can't--

00:45:00.495 --> 00:45:04.260
I don't remember
the name, Glenn--

00:45:04.260 --> 00:45:06.685
[SOBBING SOUNDS]

00:45:11.550 --> 00:45:15.042
She just-- I'm like, oh, she's
watching "The Walking Dead."

00:45:15.042 --> 00:45:16.250
I've never watched that show.

00:45:16.250 --> 00:45:18.360
I don't-- maybe I shouldn't
be letting my kids watch that

00:45:18.360 --> 00:45:18.859
show.

00:45:18.859 --> 00:45:19.950
I don't know.

00:45:19.950 --> 00:45:26.790
But she is beyond herself
with grief, genuinely.

00:45:26.790 --> 00:45:27.990
She's a smart kid.

00:45:27.990 --> 00:45:32.520
And I say, Honey first
of all, he didn't die.

00:45:32.520 --> 00:45:34.980
I hear you talk about
this guy all the time.

00:45:34.980 --> 00:45:36.540
I know people that
write scripts,

00:45:36.540 --> 00:45:37.830
this guy didn't die, OK?

00:45:37.830 --> 00:45:40.790
This is the last show
of the season, trust me.

00:45:40.790 --> 00:45:41.820
He didn't die.

00:45:41.820 --> 00:45:44.940
They just want you to think so.

00:45:44.940 --> 00:45:49.800
But she could not connect--

00:45:49.800 --> 00:45:54.210
she's smart, but they're so
disconnected from reality.

00:45:54.210 --> 00:45:57.450
It affected her so much.

00:45:57.450 --> 00:45:59.970
And it's easier to connect
to things like that.

00:45:59.970 --> 00:46:02.190
Now, when I talked to her
about real things that

00:46:02.190 --> 00:46:06.300
are happening in the world
and these terrible tragedies,

00:46:06.300 --> 00:46:08.040
she doesn't have
the same reaction.

00:46:08.040 --> 00:46:12.280
I mean, maybe part of it
is a defense mechanism.

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:15.000
It's not that she isn't
concerned about those things,

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:17.220
but it's--

00:46:17.220 --> 00:46:20.280
that is-- that's not
good that that happened.

00:46:20.280 --> 00:46:22.570
But it's not this--

00:46:22.570 --> 00:46:26.550
and so it bewilders
me sometimes.

00:46:26.550 --> 00:46:28.140
But when it comes
to parents, right, I

00:46:28.140 --> 00:46:30.056
say maybe I shouldn't
let her watch that show.

00:46:30.056 --> 00:46:32.807
Now, I think it's OK for
her to watch that show.

00:46:32.807 --> 00:46:34.890
It's probably something I
should have watched so I

00:46:34.890 --> 00:46:37.420
could make that determination.

00:46:37.420 --> 00:46:39.540
But I talk with other
parents about these issues

00:46:39.540 --> 00:46:42.194
and I'll mention how I found
Heather posting something

00:46:42.194 --> 00:46:44.610
inappropriate and so I took
her phone away for six months.

00:46:44.610 --> 00:46:50.254
And I get this, you took
your daughter's phone?

00:46:50.254 --> 00:46:51.170
I could never do that.

00:46:51.170 --> 00:46:52.378
Oh my God, she would hate me.

00:46:52.378 --> 00:46:53.266
My kid would hate me.

00:46:53.266 --> 00:46:55.450
I'm like, well, your kid's 12.

00:46:55.450 --> 00:46:57.200
I mean, and I'm not
judging other parents.

00:46:57.200 --> 00:46:59.100
Everyone has their
own things going on.

00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:01.400
But it goes back to
this accountability

00:47:01.400 --> 00:47:02.660
and responsibility.

00:47:02.660 --> 00:47:05.690
I mean, you have
to be willing to--

00:47:05.690 --> 00:47:07.190
my advice to parents,
you have to be

00:47:07.190 --> 00:47:08.900
willing to not be
their best friend

00:47:08.900 --> 00:47:11.211
because you have to
be their parent first.

00:47:11.211 --> 00:47:12.710
And later in life,
hopefully they'll

00:47:12.710 --> 00:47:15.127
realize that you were
their best friend

00:47:15.127 --> 00:47:16.460
and really looking out for them.

00:47:16.460 --> 00:47:21.064
But we all survived without
phones and computers

00:47:21.064 --> 00:47:21.980
when we were that age.

00:47:21.980 --> 00:47:23.490
And so you have to--

00:47:23.490 --> 00:47:28.520
and my advice to the
students, every time I'm

00:47:28.520 --> 00:47:32.361
talking with students, I
always hold up my journal

00:47:32.361 --> 00:47:33.860
and I ask them, how
many of people--

00:47:33.860 --> 00:47:36.930
how many people in
this room journal?

00:47:36.930 --> 00:47:37.460
OK.

00:47:37.460 --> 00:47:39.150
I always say, everybody
should journal,

00:47:39.150 --> 00:47:40.570
even if it's one or
two sentences a night.

00:47:40.570 --> 00:47:41.820
And I don't do it every night.

00:47:41.820 --> 00:47:44.210
Sometimes I'm too exhausted.

00:47:44.210 --> 00:47:46.940
But the good thing
about journaling,

00:47:46.940 --> 00:47:49.790
I always say you do it with
a real paper and a pen.

00:47:49.790 --> 00:47:53.180
Why do you think it's
with a real paper and pen?

00:47:53.180 --> 00:47:54.950
They want to go
to their devices.

00:47:54.950 --> 00:47:56.690
But if you go to
your device, you're

00:47:56.690 --> 00:47:59.030
going to be bombarded by
all this stuff-- some good,

00:47:59.030 --> 00:48:00.450
a lot bad.

00:48:00.450 --> 00:48:03.110
And that's the noise,
this noise of society.

00:48:03.110 --> 00:48:04.770
What are your thoughts?

00:48:04.770 --> 00:48:06.440
What are you thinking?

00:48:06.440 --> 00:48:09.500
Get away from all the
influence and figure out

00:48:09.500 --> 00:48:12.064
what your place is in this
world, what you want to do.

00:48:12.064 --> 00:48:12.980
SACHIT EGAN: For sure.

00:48:12.980 --> 00:48:15.500
You talk about your brother
being your protector all

00:48:15.500 --> 00:48:17.940
the time and you see
it in the pictures,

00:48:17.940 --> 00:48:19.940
you see it in stories,
you share it in the book.

00:48:19.940 --> 00:48:22.610
And I wondered if
his inclination

00:48:22.610 --> 00:48:25.670
to think about these deep
things at a younger age

00:48:25.670 --> 00:48:28.520
was in part because he
was a protector for you.

00:48:28.520 --> 00:48:31.040
He was, in a way, I think
trying to self parent a bit

00:48:31.040 --> 00:48:33.920
and provide some positive
influence in your life

00:48:33.920 --> 00:48:35.270
and help you, as well.

00:48:35.270 --> 00:48:38.390
And so he was taking that
responsibility at a young age,

00:48:38.390 --> 00:48:41.420
younger than most
people are comfortable.

00:48:41.420 --> 00:48:43.220
And now you're encouraging
kids to journal

00:48:43.220 --> 00:48:45.345
and do what Chris did in
taking some accountability

00:48:45.345 --> 00:48:47.420
and responsibility
for their own selves.

00:48:47.420 --> 00:48:49.240
But you also talk
about parents and I

00:48:49.240 --> 00:48:51.440
think what I hear you
saying is, parents,

00:48:51.440 --> 00:48:54.620
it might suck if your
daughter hates you for a day,

00:48:54.620 --> 00:48:55.610
but that's your kid.

00:48:55.610 --> 00:48:56.270
CARINE MCCANDLESS:
Well, she might

00:48:56.270 --> 00:48:57.520
hate you loner than a day.

00:48:57.520 --> 00:48:58.940
But however long it takes.

00:48:58.940 --> 00:48:59.930
SACHIT EGAN: Right.

00:48:59.930 --> 00:49:01.070
But I hear you
saying to parents,

00:49:01.070 --> 00:49:03.570
take some responsibility to
have that difficult conversation

00:49:03.570 --> 00:49:06.077
instead of just batting your
eye or looking another way.

00:49:06.077 --> 00:49:07.535
We all need to be
more responsible,

00:49:07.535 --> 00:49:09.410
is that what you're saying?

00:49:09.410 --> 00:49:10.451
CARINE MCCANDLESS: Right.

00:49:10.451 --> 00:49:14.540
And I'm not stellar
at all of this myself.

00:49:14.540 --> 00:49:18.050
We, I put we in
this including me.

00:49:18.050 --> 00:49:21.060
It's tough for parents of--

00:49:21.060 --> 00:49:24.710
I'm 45 years old and I updated
some apps the other day.

00:49:24.710 --> 00:49:27.770
I have no clue how the hell
they use these things now,

00:49:27.770 --> 00:49:29.480
but my 11-year-old
could pick up my phone

00:49:29.480 --> 00:49:32.240
and intuitively
just figure it out.

00:49:32.240 --> 00:49:36.440
So a lot of times, when I talk
to parents about social media,

00:49:36.440 --> 00:49:39.840
they, oh, I don't even
understand how all that works.

00:49:39.840 --> 00:49:41.840
Some of them have the
attitude of you know what?

00:49:41.840 --> 00:49:43.970
You've just got
to trust your kid.

00:49:43.970 --> 00:49:46.460
But they aren't aware of
a lot of the things that

00:49:46.460 --> 00:49:50.030
are happening and the things
that those kids are exposed to.

00:49:50.030 --> 00:49:51.410
So you have to be
willing to have

00:49:51.410 --> 00:49:52.970
the uncomfortable
conversations, you

00:49:52.970 --> 00:49:55.070
have to be willing
to take the phone,

00:49:55.070 --> 00:49:57.140
you have to be,
unfortunately, willing

00:49:57.140 --> 00:50:00.950
to learn how Snapchat works.

00:50:00.950 --> 00:50:01.460
You do.

00:50:01.460 --> 00:50:03.530
If you're going to give
them the access to it,

00:50:03.530 --> 00:50:04.340
you've got to be willing to--

00:50:04.340 --> 00:50:06.260
but let me make a
point here about Chris.

00:50:06.260 --> 00:50:09.080
You said that I encourage
kids to do it Chris did.

00:50:09.080 --> 00:50:11.397
Chris died out in the
middle of the wilderness.

00:50:14.140 --> 00:50:17.710
So I encourage-- people tell
me, I get messages to people

00:50:17.710 --> 00:50:20.650
all over the world and people
say that your brother changed

00:50:20.650 --> 00:50:22.380
my life.

00:50:22.380 --> 00:50:28.980
And I see where Chris inspires
people to make positive changes

00:50:28.980 --> 00:50:30.090
in their lives.

00:50:30.090 --> 00:50:32.004
But when someone tells
me and they come to me

00:50:32.004 --> 00:50:33.420
and they're in
tears and they say,

00:50:33.420 --> 00:50:39.190
your brother saved my
life, I say to them,

00:50:39.190 --> 00:50:42.890
Chris died in 1992.

00:50:42.890 --> 00:50:45.090
He couldn't do that for you.

00:50:45.090 --> 00:50:48.440
Now, he can be a spark
that lights a fuel in you

00:50:48.440 --> 00:50:51.380
to do that for
yourself, but own it.

00:50:51.380 --> 00:50:53.810
You did that for yourself.

00:50:53.810 --> 00:51:00.410
And so yeah, I want
people to be influenced

00:51:00.410 --> 00:51:08.540
by Chris' desire to have
a purpose in life, right?

00:51:08.540 --> 00:51:12.470
He died so young, but he's
influenced so many people

00:51:12.470 --> 00:51:17.280
without even trying to,
and for the most part

00:51:17.280 --> 00:51:18.920
in very positive ways.

00:51:18.920 --> 00:51:22.140
But Chris was also accountable.

00:51:22.140 --> 00:51:26.650
He knew that he put himself
in a very difficult situation

00:51:26.650 --> 00:51:30.130
and he didn't blame
anybody else for it.

00:51:30.130 --> 00:51:34.810
I talk a lot about our childhood
and my parents in my book,

00:51:34.810 --> 00:51:37.960
but I don't blame
them for his death.

00:51:37.960 --> 00:51:42.950
Chris put himself out in
the wilderness unprepared.

00:51:42.950 --> 00:51:46.370
I do hold him accountable
for his disappearance,

00:51:46.370 --> 00:51:48.970
and that's a very
different thing.

00:51:48.970 --> 00:51:50.910
So one of the greatest
lessons that people

00:51:50.910 --> 00:51:57.390
can learn from Chris and kids
of that age is to be accountable

00:51:57.390 --> 00:51:58.770
and to have that self-awareness.

00:51:58.770 --> 00:52:02.700
Because at the end, I don't
know if we have time for it,

00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:06.650
but Chris--

00:52:06.650 --> 00:52:09.670
I put some more slides up
here simply because there's

00:52:09.670 --> 00:52:13.240
a lot of things-- that's
me hiking to the- us,

00:52:13.240 --> 00:52:14.270
Chris on the road.

00:52:17.020 --> 00:52:23.990
So just very quickly,
at the end of the movie,

00:52:23.990 --> 00:52:26.750
they show this note.

00:52:26.750 --> 00:52:29.750
So this is the note
that Chris wrote

00:52:29.750 --> 00:52:32.049
when he knew he was dying,
I have had a happy life

00:52:32.049 --> 00:52:32.840
and thank the Lord.

00:52:32.840 --> 00:52:34.340
Goodbye and may God bless all.

00:52:38.090 --> 00:52:44.740
So he had taken that page
out of one of his books

00:52:44.740 --> 00:52:49.000
and on the opposite
was this excerpt

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:52.550
from a poem by Robinson Jeffers
from "Wise Men in the Bad

00:52:52.550 --> 00:52:53.050
Hours."

00:52:53.050 --> 00:52:55.260
It reads, "Death's
a fierce meadowlark,

00:52:55.260 --> 00:52:57.100
but to die having
made something more

00:52:57.100 --> 00:52:59.080
equal to the centuries
than muscle and bone

00:52:59.080 --> 00:53:00.235
is mostly to shed weakness.

00:53:03.030 --> 00:53:04.660
The mountains are dead stone.

00:53:04.660 --> 00:53:07.350
The people admire or
hate their stature,

00:53:07.350 --> 00:53:09.420
their insolent quietness.

00:53:09.420 --> 00:53:12.250
The mountains are not
softened nor troubled

00:53:12.250 --> 00:53:15.730
and a few dead men's thoughts
have the same temper."

00:53:15.730 --> 00:53:18.660
Chris didn't do anything
without a purpose.

00:53:18.660 --> 00:53:20.610
He didn't just randomly
pull this one page

00:53:20.610 --> 00:53:22.795
and decide to write the
last words that he's

00:53:22.795 --> 00:53:24.790
going to write in his life.

00:53:24.790 --> 00:53:26.380
And he also didn't
do it for us, he

00:53:26.380 --> 00:53:27.630
didn't do it for anybody else.

00:53:27.630 --> 00:53:28.580
He didn't know that
anybody was ever

00:53:28.580 --> 00:53:29.795
going to find this or care.

00:53:32.640 --> 00:53:34.680
When the students
take pictures, what's

00:53:34.680 --> 00:53:38.220
the first thing we all do
now when we take a picture?

00:53:38.220 --> 00:53:39.949
SACHIT EGAN: Uploaded it.

00:53:39.949 --> 00:53:42.240
CARINE MCCANDLESS: Maybe you
since you work for Google.

00:53:42.240 --> 00:53:44.350
I haven't uploaded
pictures in a long time.

00:53:44.350 --> 00:53:45.250
I'm so behind.

00:53:45.250 --> 00:53:45.750
No.

00:53:45.750 --> 00:53:48.892
The first thing we do is
we look at the picture.

00:53:48.892 --> 00:53:49.850
We look at the picture.

00:53:49.850 --> 00:53:52.850
Did we get the images that
we're looking for, right?

00:53:52.850 --> 00:53:56.150
But Chris, these pictures that
people see online of Chris,

00:53:56.150 --> 00:53:59.310
Chris never saw these pictures.

00:53:59.310 --> 00:54:01.939
That was back in the day where
you had this thing called film

00:54:01.939 --> 00:54:03.980
on a roll and you had to
take it to the drugstore

00:54:03.980 --> 00:54:05.820
and get it developed and
you don't even know what

00:54:05.820 --> 00:54:06.510
the images--

00:54:06.510 --> 00:54:10.325
but Chris, there aren't five
of these pictures, there's one.

00:54:10.325 --> 00:54:11.950
He didn't take it,
let me make sure I'm

00:54:11.950 --> 00:54:13.060
getting the right shot.

00:54:13.060 --> 00:54:15.820
And Jon writes
about, which is not

00:54:15.820 --> 00:54:19.270
a picture I have up here because
it's too difficult for me,

00:54:19.270 --> 00:54:21.250
and I read it at the
end of my Ted Talk,

00:54:21.250 --> 00:54:25.450
I believe, but he writes
about this photo of Chris,

00:54:25.450 --> 00:54:28.880
the last photo that
Chris takes of himself,

00:54:28.880 --> 00:54:30.760
and he talks about
how he's standing

00:54:30.760 --> 00:54:33.080
beneath the
highlights of the sky

00:54:33.080 --> 00:54:38.920
and if he feels betrayed that
his body has let him down.

00:54:38.920 --> 00:54:43.440
I'm totally-- Jon wrote it
so beautifully and I just--

00:54:43.440 --> 00:54:44.190
I have it here.

00:54:47.600 --> 00:54:49.070
Let me just do service to this.

00:54:49.070 --> 00:54:50.028
It just takes a minute.

00:54:56.310 --> 00:54:59.760
So he talks about this and
he quotes Jeffers' poem

00:54:59.760 --> 00:55:03.901
and he says, "One
of his last acts

00:55:03.901 --> 00:55:06.150
was to take a picture of
himself standing near the bus

00:55:06.150 --> 00:55:09.304
under the high Alaska sky, one
hand holding his final note

00:55:09.304 --> 00:55:10.970
toward the camera
lens, the other raised

00:55:10.970 --> 00:55:13.280
in a brave beatific farewell.

00:55:13.280 --> 00:55:18.060
His face is horribly
emaciated, almost skeletal.

00:55:18.060 --> 00:55:21.380
But if he pitied himself in
those last difficult hours

00:55:21.380 --> 00:55:25.250
because he was so young,
because he was alone,

00:55:25.250 --> 00:55:26.740
because his body
had betrayed him

00:55:26.740 --> 00:55:29.210
and his will had
let him down, it's

00:55:29.210 --> 00:55:32.020
not apparent from
the photograph.

00:55:32.020 --> 00:55:34.870
He is smiling in the
picture and there is no

00:55:34.870 --> 00:55:37.570
mistaking the look in his eyes.

00:55:37.570 --> 00:55:43.880
Chris McCandless was at peace,
serene as a monk gone to God."

00:55:43.880 --> 00:55:48.160
That picture that Jon's talking
about, it's not this one,

00:55:48.160 --> 00:55:52.900
is both the hardest and
the most wonderful picture

00:55:52.900 --> 00:55:53.830
for me to look at.

00:55:53.830 --> 00:55:57.557
It's a good pain, I call it,
because I see he's dying,

00:55:57.557 --> 00:55:58.140
he's skeletal.

00:56:00.660 --> 00:56:03.420
But he does have
this genuine smile.

00:56:03.420 --> 00:56:05.280
And there's one shot.

00:56:05.280 --> 00:56:08.192
He didn't take a bunch hoping,
oh, am I going to get it right?

00:56:08.192 --> 00:56:09.900
Am I going to put the
right thing across?

00:56:09.900 --> 00:56:12.240
He's not thinking
about anybody else.

00:56:12.240 --> 00:56:14.910
That's just pure emotion
coming out of him and it's real

00:56:14.910 --> 00:56:17.782
and it's genuine and it happens
to be because of his faith.

00:56:21.220 --> 00:56:25.690
But for any of us, whether we
live a young number of years

00:56:25.690 --> 00:56:28.240
or whether we live
into our 80s and 90s,

00:56:28.240 --> 00:56:31.570
to have that peace at
the end of our life,

00:56:31.570 --> 00:56:37.940
whenever that time comes, to
me that's what it's all about--

00:56:37.940 --> 00:56:39.630
to be at peace with
the past you've

00:56:39.630 --> 00:56:43.602
chosen in life in the way
you've lived your life, what

00:56:43.602 --> 00:56:44.810
the purpose of your life was.

00:56:44.810 --> 00:56:49.550
And although Chris'
life was short

00:56:49.550 --> 00:56:51.560
and although he
was so devastated

00:56:51.560 --> 00:56:54.020
to be losing his life
at such a young age,

00:56:54.020 --> 00:56:59.430
and I know this from reading
his journal, he was at peace--

00:56:59.430 --> 00:57:02.250
not because he was dying,
but because he had lived

00:57:02.250 --> 00:57:04.270
and the way he had lived.

00:57:04.270 --> 00:57:08.800
And to me, that's my advice for
students is use those journals,

00:57:08.800 --> 00:57:12.940
figure out who you are,
figure out what you want to be

00:57:12.940 --> 00:57:14.500
and what you want to do.

00:57:14.500 --> 00:57:16.240
And when that day
comes for you, and it's

00:57:16.240 --> 00:57:18.156
going to come for all
of us unless you guys at

00:57:18.156 --> 00:57:19.480
Google here figure out--

00:57:19.480 --> 00:57:22.360
I mean, it might be coming,
I'm sure you're working on it--

00:57:22.360 --> 00:57:24.130
better find us to
some other planets

00:57:24.130 --> 00:57:26.009
because it's getting
a little crowded.

00:57:26.009 --> 00:57:27.550
SACHIT EGAN: Talk
to Elan about that.

00:57:27.550 --> 00:57:28.550
CARINE MCCANDLESS: Yeah.

00:57:28.550 --> 00:57:30.480
We'll talk to Elan about it.

00:57:30.480 --> 00:57:32.797
But that's my point.

00:57:32.797 --> 00:57:35.380
SACHIT EGAN: Do you see any of
Chris' traits in your children?

00:57:38.280 --> 00:57:41.180
CARINE MCCANDLESS: Well, yes.

00:57:41.180 --> 00:57:48.860
So Heather isn't
biologically my child.

00:57:48.860 --> 00:57:49.670
I adopted her.

00:57:52.460 --> 00:57:55.610
So as far as traits if you
mean that have traveled down

00:57:55.610 --> 00:57:57.500
biologically.

00:57:57.500 --> 00:58:04.340
Christiana, my youngest,
she is named after Chris.

00:58:04.340 --> 00:58:07.230
She has Down syndrome.

00:58:07.230 --> 00:58:08.820
Doesn't matter.

00:58:08.820 --> 00:58:11.850
Nothing is going
to stop this kid.

00:58:11.850 --> 00:58:14.430
Things that remind
me of Chris in her

00:58:14.430 --> 00:58:17.009
are why can't I go
climb a 100-foot oak

00:58:17.009 --> 00:58:18.300
tree to play with the raccoons?

00:58:18.300 --> 00:58:20.130
I don't understand
why that's a problem.

00:58:20.130 --> 00:58:25.470
I mean, but there's also
just this purity in her.

00:58:25.470 --> 00:58:29.480
Obviously, she doesn't have--

00:58:29.480 --> 00:58:31.740
I don't know, she's only
11, I guess we'll see.

00:58:31.740 --> 00:58:35.660
But I mean, her deep thoughts
right now are about princesses.

00:58:38.300 --> 00:58:42.840
But there's a light
and a pureness in her

00:58:42.840 --> 00:58:45.521
that I definitely recognize.

00:58:45.521 --> 00:58:46.020
Yeah.

00:58:48.814 --> 00:58:49.772
SACHIT EGAN: Very cool.

00:58:49.772 --> 00:58:52.547
Anybody else?

00:58:52.547 --> 00:58:54.380
CARINE MCCANDLESS: Did
I talk so much that I

00:58:54.380 --> 00:58:56.079
answered all of your questions?

00:58:56.079 --> 00:58:57.120
SACHIT EGAN: That's fair.

00:58:57.120 --> 00:58:59.300
I'll ask you a final one then
and we can go to book signing.

00:58:59.300 --> 00:58:59.900
CARINE MCCANDLESS:
Are you guys going

00:58:59.900 --> 00:59:02.410
straight to a conference room
to figure out this whole issue

00:59:02.410 --> 00:59:03.331
after this?

00:59:03.331 --> 00:59:04.580
SACHIT EGAN: We've got a book.

00:59:04.580 --> 00:59:06.954
CARINE MCCANDLESS: How to
populate good influences coming

00:59:06.954 --> 00:59:07.970
into people's pages.

00:59:07.970 --> 00:59:09.180
SACHIT EGAN: This is
one you and I have

00:59:09.180 --> 00:59:10.263
talked about a little bit.

00:59:10.263 --> 00:59:14.530
But when I went and
visited the bus in 2012,

00:59:14.530 --> 00:59:18.680
there's some supplies and
things and notes and journals

00:59:18.680 --> 00:59:21.080
that people leave behind
for future visitors.

00:59:21.080 --> 00:59:23.000
And what was amazing
when I visited was

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:26.266
there was in a plastic bag
one of Carine's journals.

00:59:26.266 --> 00:59:28.640
And I think it's the one that
you had taken with you when

00:59:28.640 --> 00:59:31.680
you first visited the bus and
you'd left it there for people,

00:59:31.680 --> 00:59:33.980
I think, to write in.

00:59:33.980 --> 00:59:35.540
And getting to the
bus is not easy.

00:59:35.540 --> 00:59:37.850
It's 40 miles round trip.

00:59:37.850 --> 00:59:40.160
You have to cross two
rivers, it's the middle--

00:59:40.160 --> 00:59:44.300
the mosquitoes are insane.

00:59:44.300 --> 00:59:45.860
And I remember
we'd gotten there,

00:59:45.860 --> 00:59:47.660
we'd done a 20-mile
day that day to get

00:59:47.660 --> 00:59:49.201
to the bus and the
first thing that I

00:59:49.201 --> 00:59:52.310
see on the cover of this
journal is a Buddhist quote that

00:59:52.310 --> 00:59:54.170
said, "There is no
way to happiness,

00:59:54.170 --> 00:59:56.120
happiness is the way."

00:59:56.120 --> 00:59:58.370
And it occurred to me that
I'd taken this journey

00:59:58.370 --> 01:00:01.820
to find something at this
bus, as it did by the graffiti

01:00:01.820 --> 01:00:05.120
there hundreds, maybe
thousands of people,

01:00:05.120 --> 01:00:06.860
all seeking something.

01:00:06.860 --> 01:00:09.200
But this quote talks
about it being within us.

01:00:09.200 --> 01:00:11.180
Can you talk about it
all that has resonated

01:00:11.180 --> 01:00:12.740
with you in your life?

01:00:12.740 --> 01:00:15.260
CARINE MCCANDLESS: That's
it, self-awareness.

01:00:15.260 --> 01:00:17.870
If you don't get away from
that noise of society sometimes

01:00:17.870 --> 01:00:20.060
and you don't have
that self-awareness.

01:00:20.060 --> 01:00:23.510
I mean, it breaks right down
to kids going to college

01:00:23.510 --> 01:00:26.210
or they don't go to college,
they go into a career.

01:00:26.210 --> 01:00:27.710
Are they doing that
they want to do,

01:00:27.710 --> 01:00:30.206
or are they doing what
they were told to do?

01:00:30.206 --> 01:00:31.580
Are they following
their own path

01:00:31.580 --> 01:00:34.880
or are they following a path
that was laid out for them?

01:00:34.880 --> 01:00:39.035
It's not just academics,
it's also socially.

01:00:41.930 --> 01:00:45.530
All of these influences that
are all over the internet

01:00:45.530 --> 01:00:48.920
are determining these
paths and these choices

01:00:48.920 --> 01:00:52.737
that we all make all the time
and the kids are watching it.

01:00:52.737 --> 01:00:54.570
SACHIT EGAN: A round
of applause for Carine.

01:00:54.570 --> 01:00:55.611
Thank you for being here.

01:00:55.611 --> 01:00:57.920
[APPLAUSE]

